{"id":"1908.08646","submitter":"Yoichi Murakami","authors":"Yutaka Ikeda, Kazuki Fukui and Yoichi Murakami","title":"Integration of Liquid Thermoelectrochemical Conversion into Forced\n  Convection Cooling","comments":"35 pages of main body + 20 pages of supplementary information","journal-ref":"Phys. Chem. Chem. Phys., 2019, 21, 25838-25848","doi":"10.1039/C9CP05028K","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.chem-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Forced convection cooling is important in numerous technologies ranging from\nmicroprocessors in data centers to turbines and engines; active cooling is\nessential in these situations. However, active transfer of heat or thermal\nenergy under a large temperature difference promptly destroys the exergy, which\nis the free-energy component of thermal energy, and this issue has remained\nunaddressed. Herein, we describe a thermoelectrochemical conversion to\npartially recover presently lost exergy in forced convection cooling. We design\na test cell in which an electrolyte liquid is forced through a channel formed\nbetween two parallel electrodes and the hot-side electrode simulates an object\nto be cooled. Our investigations show that the narrower interelectrode channels\nafford higher cooling and power generation performances. The mass transfer\nresistance is the most dominant type of resistance for all the conditions\ntested and the charge transfer kinetics is likely to be controlled by\nviscosity. The dependence of the generated power on the flow rate is caused by\nthe change in the diffusion coefficient of redox species with temperature. As\nan evaluation measure for such forced-flow thermocells, the gain (\\Lambda)\n--defined as the ratio of the generated power to the hydrodynamic pumping work\nrequired to force the liquid through the cell-- is introduced. \\Lambda is above\nunity in a certain flow rate region. This demonstrates that such a system can\ngenerate more electric power than the pump work required to drive the liquid\nthrough the cell, suggesting its potential to partly recover presently lost\nexergy of thermal energy as electricity.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 23 Aug 2019 03:14:25 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-01-08"}
